The '''Belgium national football team'''{{efn|{{langx|nl|Belgisch nationaal voetbalelftal}}<br />{{langx|fr|Équipe nationale belge de football}}<br />{{langx|de|Belgische Fußballnationalmannschaft}}}} has represented [[Belgium]] in men's international [[Association football|football]] since [[Évence Coppée Trophy|their maiden match]] in 1904. The squad is under the global jurisdiction of [[FIFA]] and is governed in Europe by [[UEFA]]—both of which were co-founded by the Belgian team's supervising body, the [[Royal Belgian Football Association]]. Periods of regular Belgian representation at the highest international level, from 1920 to 1938, from 1980 to 2002 and again from 2014 onwards, have alternated with mostly unsuccessful qualification rounds. Most of Belgium's home matches are played at the [[King Baudouin Stadium]] in [[Brussels]].

Belgium's national team have participated in three quadrennial major football competitions. It appeared in fourteen [[FIFA World Cup]]s and six [[UEFA European Championship]]s, and featured at three Olympic football tournaments, including the [[Football at the 1920 Summer Olympics|1920 Summer Olympics]] which they won. Other notable performances are victories over four [[FIFA World Cup#Results|reigning world champions]]—West Germany, Brazil, Argentina and France—between 1954 and 2002. Belgium has long-standing football rivalries with its Dutch and French counterparts, having played both teams nearly every year from 1905 to 1967. The squad has been known as the Red Devils since 1906; its fan club is named "1895".

Belgium finished in third place as hosts at [[UEFA Euro 1972]]. After that, they experienced two [[golden generation]]s. In the first period, which lasted from the 1980s to the early 1990s, the team finished as runners-up at [[UEFA Euro 1980]] and fourth in the [[1986 FIFA World Cup]]. In the second, under the guidance of [[Marc Wilmots]] and later [[Roberto Martínez]] in the 2010s, Belgium topped the [[FIFA Men's World Ranking|FIFA World Ranking]] for the first time in November 2015 and finished third at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]]. To date, Belgium is the only national team to top the FIFA ranking without having won a World Cup or continental trophy.

==History==
{{Main|History of the Belgium national football team}}

===Early history===
Belgium was one of the first mainland European countries to play association football, with the earliest recorded example of its practice in Belgium dating back to 1863.<ref>See:* {{harvnb|Goldblatt|2008|p=120}}, * {{harvnb|de Vries|2007|p=57}}, * {{harvnb|Kassimeris|2007|p=12}}.</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=http://eoswetenschap.eu/artikel/belgische-voetbalgeschiedenis-begon-gent |title=Belgische voetbalgeschiedenis begon in Gent |trans-title=Belgian football history began in Ghent |journal=[[Eos (newspaper)|Eos]] |first=Dries |last=Vanysacker |date=21 May 2015 |language=nl |access-date=13 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625095029/http://eoswetenschap.eu/artikel/belgische-voetbalgeschiedenis-begon-gent |archive-date=25 June 2016}}</ref>
[[File:BelgiumNFT1901.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.2|alt=Football team in uniform|The first Belgium A-squad in 1901 featured four Englishmen.]]
On 11 October 1900, [[K. Beerschot V.A.C.|Beerschot AC]] honorary president Jorge Díaz announced that [[Antwerp]] would host a series of challenge matches between Europe's best football teams.{{sfn|Guldemont|Deps|1995|p=64}} After some organisational problems, on 28 April 1901, Beerschot's pitch hosted [[1901 Coupe Vanden Abeele|its first tournament]], in which a Belgian selection and a Dutch team made up of players from third-level sides led by ex-footballer [[Cees van Hasselt]] contested the [[Belgium vs Netherlands Cups#Coupe Vanden Abeele|Coupe Vanden Abeele]].<ref name=Vanden>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tablesc/coupe-vdab.html |title=Coupe Vanden Abeele |date=9 June 2022 |accessdate=14 January 2024 }}</ref> Naturally, the hosts had little trouble claiming the cup, defeating the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] by 8–0.<ref name=Vanden/>{{sfn|Fraiponts|Willocx|2003}}<ref name="TrouwCVA">{{cite news |title=Interlandvoetbal om 'koperen dingetje'/Sporteeuw (2) – 1901 |trans-title=International football for 'the copper thingy'/Sports Century (2) – 1901 |first=Matty |last=Verkamman |url=http://www.trouw.nl/tr/nl/5009/Archief/article/detail/2649008/1999/01/09/Interlandvoetbal-om-koperen-dingetje-Sporteeuw-2---1901.dhtml |newspaper=[[Trouw]] |language=nl |date=9 January 1999 |access-date=9 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625095406/http://www.trouw.nl/tr/nl/5009/Archief/article/detail/2649008/1999/01/09/Interlandvoetbal-om-koperen-dingetje-Sporteeuw-2---1901.dhtml |archive-date=25 June 2016}}</ref> Belgium then beat the Netherlands in all three follow-up matches;{{sfn|Hubert|1980|p=13}} [[Belgium national football team results (unofficial matches)|FIFA does not recognize these results]] because Belgium fielded some English players, such as [[Herbert Potts]], who scored 12 of "Belgium's" 17 goals.<ref name=Vanden/>{{sfn|Hubert|1980|p=13}}

On 1 May 1904, the Belgians played their first official match, against [[France national football team|France]] at the [[Stade du Vivier d'Oie]] in Uccle; their draw left the Évence Coppée Trophy unclaimed.<ref name="UEFABelFra1904">{{cite web|title=Belgium v France − a 109-year-old rivalry |publisher=[[UEFA]] |date=13 August 2013 |access-date=15 August 2013 |url=https://www.uefa.com/worldcup/news/newsid=1980808.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625095456/http://www.uefa.com/worldcup/news/newsid%3D1980808.html |archive-date=25 June 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Twenty days later, the [[Football association|football board]]s of both countries were among the seven FIFA founders.<ref>{{cite web |title=History of FIFA – Foundation |publisher=[[FIFA]] |access-date=16 May 2014 |url=https://www.fifa.com/about-fifa/who-we-are/history/index.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625095542/http://www.fifa.com/about-fifa/who-we-are/history/index.html |archive-date=25 June 2016}}</ref>{{sfn|Parrish|Nauright|2014|p=xv}} At that time, the Belgian squad was chosen by a committee chaired by [[Édouard de Laveleye]], who usually drew from the country's six or seven major clubs.{{sfn|Boin|1945}} Belgium would play twice a year against the Netherlands beginning from 1905 onwards, generally once in Antwerp and once in [[Rotterdam]]. From these beginnings until 1925, [[Belgium vs Netherlands Cups|Belgian-Dutch cup trophies]] would be awarded in the "[[Low Countries derby]]".{{sfn|Fraiponts|Willocx|2003}}

In 1906, the national team received the nickname ''Red Devils'' because of their red jerseys,{{sfn|Guldemont|Deps|1995|p=65}} and four years later, Scottish ex-footballer [[William Maxwell (footballer)|William Maxwell]] replaced the UBSSA committee as their manager.<ref name="manrsssf" /> From 1912, UBSSA governed football only and was renamed UBSFA.{{efn|UBSFA was the acronym for the organisation's French name: ''Union Belge des Sociétés de Football-Association''.<br />In 1920 it received the title of "Royal Union" for its 25th year of existence, and hence became the Royal Belgian Football Association.<ref>{{cite web|title=Historique de l'URBSFA |trans-title=History of the RBFA |publisher=[[Royal Belgian Football Association|RBFA]] |language=fr |url=http://www.belgianfootball.be/fr/historique-de-lurbsfa |access-date=31 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120507062324/http://www.belgianfootball.be/fr/historique-de-lurbsfa |archive-date=7 May 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>}}<ref name="RBFAhist"/>{{sfn|Henshaw|1979|p=75}} During the Great War, the national team only played  [[Belgium national football team results – unofficial matches|unrecognized friendlies]], with matches in and against France.<ref name="results" /><ref name="DT210316">{{cite news |url=http://www.delpher.nl/nl/kranten/view?coll=ddd&identifier=ddd%3A110548702%3Ampeg21%3Aa0098 |newspaper=[[De Telegraaf]] |via=[[Delpher]] |title=Frankrijk–België |trans-title=France–Belgium |language=nl |date=21 March 1916 |access-date=11 June 2015}}</ref>

===Olympic gold and World Cup struggles===
[[File:1920 Olympic football final (Belgium v. Czechoslovakia), penalty Coppée.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.2|alt=A successful penalty kick, seen from the back of the net|In the 1920 Olympic football final at the [[Olympisch Stadion (Antwerp)|Olympisch Stadion]] in Antwerp, Robert Coppée scored a penalty kick for Belgium.]]
At the [[1920 Summer Olympics]], in their first official Olympics appearance, the ''Red Devils'' won the gold medal on home soil after [[Football at the 1920 Summer Olympics#Gold medal match|a controversial final]] in which their Czechoslovak opponents left the pitch.<ref name="ISOH"/> In the three 1920s Summer Olympic, they achieved fair results (four wins in seven matches), and played their first intercontinental match, against [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]].<ref name="results"/>

However, over the following decade, Belgium lost all of their matches at the first three FIFA World Cup final tournaments.<ref name="results"/> According to historian Richard Henshaw, "[t]he growth of [football] in Scandinavia, Central Europe, and South America left Belgium far behind".{{sfn|Henshaw|1979|p=76}} Although [[World War II]] hindered international football events in the 1940s, the Belgian team remained active with unofficial matches against squads of other [[Allies of World War II|allied nations]].<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.arch.be/docs/catalogues/catalogus_belgium-in-exile.pdf |journal=Catalogus van de Gelijknamige Tentoonstelling in Het Algemeen Rijksarchief te Brussel |title=Belgium in exile - Belgische regering, vluchtelingen en soldaten in Groot-Brittannië |page=31 |trans-title=Belgium in exile - Belgian government, refugees and soldiers in Great Britain |publisher=[[National Archives of Belgium]] |language=nl |access-date=18 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161218120617/http://www.arch.be/docs/catalogues/catalogus_belgium-in-exile.pdf |archive-date=18 December 2016}}</ref>

Belgium qualified for only one of eight major tournaments during the 1950s and the 1960s: the [[1954 FIFA World Cup|1954 World Cup]]. The day before the tournament began, the RBFA was among the three UEFA founders.<ref>{{cite web|title=The birth of UEFA |publisher=[[UEFA]] |first=Mark |last=Chaplin |date=5 May 2014 |access-date=28 June 2014 |url=http://www.uefa.org/60-years/news/newsid=2099394.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625100116/http://www.uefa.org/60-years/news/newsid%3D2099394.html |archive-date=25 June 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Dutch journalists considered the draw of the 1954 Belgian team in their opener against [[England national football team|England]] to be the most surprising result of that match day, even more than [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]]'s victory over the Italian "football stars".<ref name="AD180654">{{cite news |url=http://www.delpher.nl/nl/kranten/view?query=belgi%C3%AB+engeland+voetbal&facets%5Bperiode%5D%5B%5D=2%7C20e_eeuw%7C1950-1959%7C1954%7C&page=11&sortfield=date&coll=ddd&identifier=ddd%3A010404313%3Ampeg21%3Aa0108&resultsidentifier=ddd%3A010404313%3Ampeg21%3Aa0108 |newspaper=Amigoe di Curaçao |via=[[Delpher]] |title=België wist Engeland een gelijk spel af te dwingen |trans-title=Belgium managed to enforce a draw against England |language=nl |date=18 June 1954 |access-date=19 December 2016}}</ref> However, Belgium were eliminated after a loss to [[Italy national football team|Italy]] in the second (and last) group match.<ref name="rsssf54"/> Two bright spots in these decades were wins against World Cup holders: [[Germany national football team|West Germany]] in 1954, and [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] in 1963.<ref name="results"/> Between these, Belgium defeated Hungary's [[Golden Team]] in 1956.<ref name="results"/> The combination of failure in competitive matches, and success in exhibition matches, gave the Belgians the mock title of "world champions of the friendlies".<ref>{{cite web|title=Retro WK 1966: Engeland wint na meest omstreden goal van de eeuw, Duivels stranden in testmatch |trans-title=Retro WC 1966: England wins after most controversial goal of the century, Devils left stranded in test match |language=nl |url=https://www.voetbalnieuws.be/news/119769/RETRO_WK_1966:_Engeland_wint_na_meest_omstreden_goal_van_de_eeuw,_Duivels_stranden_in_testmatch |website=voetbalnieuws.be |date=31 May 2014 |access-date=19 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625100210/http://www.voetbalnieuws.be/news/119769/RETRO_WK_1966%3A_Engeland_wint_na_meest_omstreden_goal_van_de_eeuw%2C_Duivels_stranden_in_testmatch |archive-date=25 June 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{sfn|Bernhart|Houtman|2014}}
[[File:Nederland_tegen_Belgie_3-1,_Belgisch_elftal,_Heylens,_Bare,_Trappeniers,_Michiel,_Bestanddeelnr_919-0402.jpg|thumb|260px|The Belgium squad at the start of a friendly game against the Netherlands, 1966]]
The team's performance improved during the early 1970s, under manager [[Raymond Goethals]]. Fully dressed in white, as the White Devils,<ref name="WhiteDevil"/> Belgium achieved their first victories at the World Cup in [[1970 FIFA World Cup|1970]] and the Euros in [[UEFA Euro 1972|1972]], their debut.<ref name="rsssf70"/><ref name="rsssf72"/> En route to Euro 1972, they eliminated [[List of UEFA European Championship records and statistics#General statistics by tournament|reigning European champions]] Italy by winning the [[UEFA Euro 1972 quarter-finals|two-legged quarter-final]] on [[Glossary of association football terms#A|aggregate]]. At the end stage, they finished third by winning the consolation match against Hungary.<ref name="rsssf72"/> In 1973, the denial of a match-winning goal in their last [[1974 FIFA World Cup qualification]] match for UEFA Group 3 cost Belgium their appearance at the final,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/sport/wonderbaarlijke-ontsnappingen-uit-de-oranje-historie~a743458/ |title=Wonderbaarlijke ontsnappingen uit de Oranje-historie |trans-title=Miraculous escapes in Oranje history |newspaper=[[de Volkskrant]] |language=nl |date=19 November 2003 |access-date=16 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160608214932/http://www.volkskrant.nl/sport/wonderbaarlijke-ontsnappingen-uit-de-oranje-historie~a743458/ |archive-date=8 June 2016}}</ref> causing Belgium to become the only nation ever to miss a World Cup final round despite not allowing a goal during the qualifiers.{{sfn|Snyder|2001}} The next two attempts to reach a major final ([[UEFA Euro 1976|Euro 1976]] and the [[1978 FIFA World Cup]]) were also fruitless.<ref name="rsssf76">{{cite web |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/76e.html |title=European Championship 1976 |first1=Karel |last1=Stokkermans |first2=Martín |last2=Tabeira |date=20 June 2013 |access-date=24 October 2015 |website=[[RSSSF]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625100410/http://www.rsssf.com/tables/76e.html |archive-date=25 June 2016}}</ref><ref name="rsssf78">{{cite web |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/78q.html |title=World Cup 1978 Qualifying |first1=Karel |last1=Stokkermans |first2=Sergio Henrique |last2=Jarreta |date=3 January 2000 |access-date=24 October 2015 |website=[[RSSSF]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625100456/http://www.rsssf.com/tables/78q.html |archive-date=25 June 2016}}</ref>
[[File:Selectie Belgisch elftal Atomium op de achtergrond, Bestanddeelnr 929-0880.jpg|thumb|260px|The Belgian national team before a training session in 1977]]

===Golden age===
Beginning with a second-place finish at Euro 1980,<ref name="rsssf80"/> the 1980s and the early 1990s are generally considered as Belgium's first golden age.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/118096/2014-world-cup-test-belgiums-new-golden-generation |title=Why You Should (and Should Not) be Excited About Belgium's New Golden Generation |magazine=[[The New Republic]] |date=16 June 2014 |author=[[David Runciman|Runciman, David]] |access-date=5 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200726181035/https://newrepublic.com/article/118096/2014-world-cup-test-belgiums-new-golden-generation |archive-date=26 July 2020}}</ref> Coached by [[Guy Thys]], they achieved their spot in [[UEFA Euro 1980 final|the 1980 final]] with an unbeaten record in the group phase; in the final, they narrowly lost the title to West Germany 1–2.<ref name="rsssf80"/> Starting with the [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982 World Cup]], and ending with the [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002 World Cup]], the national team qualified for six consecutive World Cups.<ref name="BBC230514">{{cite web |title=2014 Fifa World Cup: Guide to Belgium's Group H |publisher=BBC |date=23 May 2014 |access-date=12 July 2016 |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/25159874 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200919203001/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/25159874 |archive-date=19 September 2020}}</ref> During this period, managers Guy Thys, [[Paul Van Himst]] and [[Robert Waseige]] each guided Belgium past the first round.<ref name="rsssf82" /><ref name="rsssf94"/><ref name="rsssf2002"/> In addition to receiving individual [[FIFA World Cup awards|FIFA recognitions]],<ref name="AllStar"/><ref name="FIFAWCAwards"/> the team reached the semi-finals of the [[1986 FIFA World Cup|1986 World Cup]] after eliminating the [[Soviet Union national football team|Soviet Union]] and [[Spain national football team|Spain]] in the [[1986 FIFA World Cup knockout stage|knockout stage]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=17 May 2024 |title=1986 Soccer World Cup Scores |url=https://www.thesoccerworldcups.com/world_cups/1986_results.php |website=thesoccerworldcups.com |language=}}</ref> [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] went through to the final after a 2–0 victory, in which their star player [[Diego Maradona]] scored both goals.<ref>{{Cite web |date=15 December 2022 |title=Why Diego Maradona against Belgium was his most complete display at the 1986 World Cup |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/3540424/2022/12/15/diego-maradona-belgium-1986-world-cup/ |website=[[The New York Times]] |language=}}</ref>
[[File:Argentina_v_belgica_1986.jpg|thumb|260px|[[Diego Maradona]] and [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] won 2–0 to knock Belgium out of the 1986 World Cup.]]
After reaching the [[UEFA Euro 1980 final|Euro 1980 final]], they were unsuccessful at subsequent European Championships, with early exits from their appearances in [[UEFA Euro 1984|1984]] and [[UEFA Euro 2000|2000]].<ref name="rsssf84det" /><ref name="rsssf2000" /> During the late 1990s, they played three friendly tournament in Morocco, Cyprus and Japan,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tablesh/hassanii-98.html |title=King Hassan II Tournament 1998 |first=Josef |last=Bobrowsky |date=14 June 2000 |access-date=20 August 2015 |website=[[RSSSF]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625100756/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesh/hassanii-98.html |archive-date=25 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Cyprus International Tournament 1999 |website=[[RSSSF]] |date=27 February 2001 |access-date=26 July 2016 |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tablesc/cypr-intltourn99.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160726150535/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/cypr-intltourn99.html |archive-date=26 July 2016}}</ref> sharing the [[Kirin Cup Soccer|1999 Kirin Cup]] with Peru in the latter.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tablesk/kirin99.html |first=José Luis |last=Pierrend |title=Kirin Cup 1999 |date=11 June 2000 |access-date=20 August 2015 |website=[[RSSSF]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625101004/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesk/kirin99.html |archive-date=25 June 2016}}</ref> Before the 2002 World Cup, Belgium defeated reigning world and European champions France.<ref name="results" /> During that World Cup, Belgium defeated [[Russia national football team|Russia]] and tied with co-host [[Japan national football team|Japan]] and [[Tunisia national football team|Tunisia]] to reach the [[2002 FIFA World Cup knockout stage|round of 16]].<ref name="rsssf2002" /> There they were eliminated by eventual world champions [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]]. Brazil coach [[Luiz Felipe Scolari]] would later state that their match against Belgium was the most difficult of the tournament.<ref>{{Cite web |date=6 December 2013 |title=Wilmots: "Tegen Brazilië zou mooi zijn" |trans-title=Wilmots: "Against Brazil would be nice" |url=https://www.gva.be/sport/voetbal/wilmots-tegen-brazilie-zou-mooi-zijn/30882646.html |website=gva.be |language=nl}}</ref>

After the 2002 World Cup, the team weakened with the loss of more veterans and coach Waseige.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gva.be/cnt/oid209124/archief-markov-belgie-verzwakt-door-vertrek-wilmots-verheyen |title=Markov: "België verzwakt door vertrek Wilmots-Verheyen" |trans-title=Markov: "Belgium weakened by departure Wilmots-Verheyen" |language=nl |newspaper=[[Gazet van Antwerpen]] |date=8 September 2002 |access-date=27 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625101049/http://www.gva.be/cnt/oid209124/archief-markov-belgie-verzwakt-door-vertrek-wilmots-verheyen |archive-date=25 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Waseige resigns as Belgium coach |website=BreakingNews.ie |date=17 June 2002 |access-date=15 March 2014 |url=http://www.breakingnews.ie/sport/soccer/waseige-resigns-as-belgium-coach-55972.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151121175817/http://www.breakingnews.ie/sport/soccer/waseige-resigns-as-belgium-coach-55972.html |archive-date=21 November 2015}}</ref> They missed out five successive major tournaments from [[UEFA Euro 2004]] until [[UEFA Euro 2012]], and went through an equal number of head coaches.<ref name="HN060612">{{cite web |url=http://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20120606_104 |title=Overzicht Belgische bondscoaches |trans-title=Overview Belgian national team coaches |language=nl |first=Maarten |last=Delvaux |newspaper=[[Het Nieuwsblad]] |date=6 June 2012 |access-date=18 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160721102440/http://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20120606_104 |archive-date=21 July 2016}}</ref> A 2005 win over reigning European champions [[Greece national football team|Greece]] meant nothing but a small comfort.<ref name="results"/> In between, a promising new generation was maturing at the [[2007 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2007 European U-21 Championship]]; [[Belgium national under-21 football team|Belgium's squad]] qualified for the following year's [[2008 Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]] in [[Beijing]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.standaard.be/cnt/i81dm9vn |title=Sterke generatie schrijft geschiedenis |trans-title=Strong generation writes history |first=Gunther |last=De Vos |newspaper=[[De Standaard]] |language=nl |date=18 June 2007 |access-date=27 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625101417/http://www.standaard.be/cnt/i81dm9vn |archive-date=25 June 2016}}</ref> where the [[Football at the 2008 Summer Olympics – Men's team squads#Belgium|Young Red Devils squad]] finished fourth.<ref name="rsssfOG2008"/> Seventeen of them appeared in the senior national team,<ref name="AllRedD" /> albeit without making an immediate impact. Belgium finished in second (and last) place at the [[Kirin Cup Soccer|Kirin Cup]] in May 2009,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tablesk/kirin09.html |title=Kirin Cup 2009 |first=Hamdan |last=Saaid |date=16 July 2009 |access-date=20 August 2015 |website=[[RSSSF]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625101516/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesk/kirin09.html |archive-date=25 June 2016}}</ref> and lost against 125th-ranked [[Armenia national football team|Armenian team]] in September 2009.<ref name="FIFA World Rankings"/> After [[Georges Leekens]]' second stint as national manager,<ref>{{cite news |title=Georges Leekens dan toch bondscoach |trans-title=Georges Leekens national manager after all |newspaper=[[Het Nieuwsblad]] |first1=Ludo |last1=Vandewalle |first2=Gunther |last2=De Vos |first3=Ki. |last3=V. |language=nl |date=3 May 2010 |access-date=10 July 2013 |url=https://www.nieuwsblad.be/sportwereld/cnt/DMF20100503_073 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200919203229/https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20100503_073 |archive-date=19 September 2020 }}</ref><ref name="DS130512">{{cite news |title=Leekens verlaat Rode Duivels voor Club Brugge |trans-title=Leekens leaves Red Devils for Club Brugge |newspaper=[[De Standaard]] |author1=lbo |first2=Jan |last2=M. |language=nl |date=13 May 2012 |access-date=10 July 2013 |url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/DMF20120513_032}}</ref> his assistant [[Marc Wilmots]] became the caretaker in May 2012.<ref name="DS150512">{{cite news |title=Marc Wilmots voorlopig interim-bondscoach |trans-title=Marc Wilmots provisional interim national manager |newspaper=[[De Standaard]] |first1=Maarten |last1=Delvaux |first2=Bart |last2=Lagae |language=nl |date=15 May 2012 |access-date=9 July 2013 |url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/DMF20120515_070 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112182805/http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20120515_070 |archive-date=12 November 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

===Second golden age===
After two matches as interim coach, Wilmots agreed to replace Leekens as manager.<ref>{{cite news |title=Marc Wilmots is nieuwe bondscoach tot 2014 |trans-title=Marc Wilmots is new national manager until 2014 |newspaper=[[De Standaard]] |first=Jan |last=M. |language=nl |date=6 June 2012 |access-date=9 July 2013 |url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/DMF20120606_075 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200919203637/https://www.standaard.be/cnt/DMF20120606_075 |archive-date=19 September 2020}}</ref> Following his appointment, the team's results improved,<ref>{{cite news|title=Argentina go second, Belgium & Uruguay rise |publisher=[[FIFA]] |date=12 September 2013 |access-date=12 September 2013 |url=https://www.fifa.com/fifa-world-ranking/news/y=2013/m=9/news=argentina-second-belgium-uruguay-rise-2172489.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626093801/http://www.fifa.com/fifa-world-ranking/news/y%3D2013/m%3D9/news%3Dargentina-second-belgium-uruguay-rise-2172489.html |archive-date=26 June 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> such that some foreign media regarded it as another Belgian golden generation.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Why Belgium is the hottest country in football |journal=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |first=Tim |last=Adams |date=24 August 2013 |access-date=15 September 2013 |url=http://www.esquire.co.uk/culture/features/3834/why-belgium-has-the-most-exciting-footballers-in-the-world/ |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130919103648/http://www.esquire.co.uk/culture/features/3834/why-belgium-has-the-most-exciting-footballers-in-the-world/ |archive-date=19 September 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Rote Teufel: Eine Goldene Generation mit königsblauer Disziplin |trans-title=Red Devils: A golden generation with royal blue discipline |newspaper=[[Bild]] |language=de |date=11 September 2013 |access-date=15 September 2013 |url=http://sportbild.bild.de/fussball/international/nationalmannschaft/heissestes-versprechen-in-europa-32348238.sport.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626094023/http://sportbild.bild.de/fussball/international/nationalmannschaft/heissestes-versprechen-in-europa-32348238.sport.html |archive-date=26 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Will Belgium win the World Cup? |first=John |last=Sinnott |publisher=CNN |date=10 September 2013 |access-date=15 September 2013 |url=http://worldsport.blogs.cnn.com/2013/09/10/will-belgium-win-the-world-cup/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626094128/http://worldsport.blogs.cnn.com/2013/09/10/will-belgium-win-the-world-cup/ |archive-date=26 June 2016}}</ref> The young Belgian squad qualified as unbeaten [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group A|group winners]] for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014 World Cup]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/2014q.html |title=World Cup 2014 Qualifying |first1=Karel |last1=Stokkermans |first2=Juan Pablo |last2=Andrés |first3=Erik Francisco |last3=Lugo |date=18 June 2015 |access-date=27 August 2015 |website=[[RSSSF]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626094221/http://www.rsssf.com/tables/2014q.html |archive-date=26 June 2016}}</ref> and earned Belgium's second-ever place in the World Cup quarter-finals with a four-match winning streak.<ref name="rsssf2014"/>
[[File:Match Algérie vs Belgique, Coupe du Monde 2014, Brésil (cropped).jpg|alt=Belgian defender maneuvering around the Algerian goal|thumb|260px|Belgium (in red) playing [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]] at the [[Mineirão]] at the 2014 World Cup]]

Belgium qualified for [[UEFA Euro 2016]] with a match to spare in October 2015,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.uefa.com/european-qualifiers/news/0253-0d80c202a5be-6911d9e51b36-1000--belgium-stroll-past-andorra-to-qualify/ |title=Belgium stroll past Andorra to qualify |publisher=[[UEFA]] |date=10 October 2015 |access-date=3 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626094303/http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season%3D2016/matches/round%3D2000446/match%3D2014042/postmatch/report/ |archive-date=26 June 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> and took No. 1 in the FIFA World Ranking for the first time in November 2015,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fifa.com/fifa-world-ranking/news/y=2015/m=11/news=belgium-go-top-chile-and-austria-soar-2730157.html |publisher=[[FIFA]] |title=Belgium go top, Chile and Austria soar |date=5 November 2015 |access-date=5 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626094459/http://www.fifa.com/fifa-world-ranking/news/y%3D2015/m%3D11/news%3Dbelgium-go-top-chile-and-austria-soar-2730157.html |archive-date=26 June 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> to stay first for five months.<ref name="FIFA World Rankings" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Belgium and Turkey claim awards, Hungary return |url=https://www.fifa.com/fifa-world-ranking/news/y=2015/m=12/news=belgium-and-turkey-claim-awards-hungary-return-2741598.html |publisher=[[FIFA]] |date=3 December 2015 |access-date=21 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160721140211/http://www.fifa.com/fifa-world-ranking/news/y%3D2015/m%3D12/news%3Dbelgium-and-turkey-claim-awards-hungary-return-2741598.html |archive-date=21 July 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> At the Euros, Belgium were eliminated in the quarter-finals by [[Wales national football team|Wales]].<ref name="FIFA World Rankings" /><ref name="EC2016Wal" /> This prompted the RBFA to dismiss Wilmots.<ref>{{cite news |author=maj |title=Marc Wilmots ontslagen als coach Rode Duivels |trans-title=Marc Wilmots dismissed as coach Red Devils |language=nl |newspaper=[[De Standaard]] |url=http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20160715_02386343 |date=15 July 2016 |access-date=15 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160721101418/http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20160715_02386343 |archive-date=21 July 2016}}</ref> In [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification|2018 World Cup qualifying]], they were seeded first in their group,<ref name="draw format">{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/worldcup/news/newsid=2257685.html |title=FIFA World Cup qualifying draw format |publisher=[[UEFA]] |date=16 June 2015 |access-date=21 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626094547/http://www.uefa.com/worldcup/news/newsid%3D2257685.html |archive-date=26 June 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=FIFA/Coca-Cola World Ranking – July 2015 (UEFA) |url=https://www.fifa.com/fifa-world-ranking/ranking-table/men/uefa.html |publisher=[[FIFA]] |date=9 July 2015 |access-date=9 July 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626094641/http://www.fifa.com/fifa-world-ranking/ranking-table/men/uefa.html |archive-date=26 June 2016}}</ref> and made the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|final tournament]] under Spanish manager [[Roberto Martínez]], becoming the first European team besides hosts [[Russia national football team|Russia]] to do so.<ref>{{cite news |title=Greece 1–2 Belgium: Visitors become first European side to qualify for World Cup with win |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/greece-vs-belgium/report/350170 |access-date=3 September 2017 |publisher=[[Sky Sports]] |date=3 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170904064646/http://www.skysports.com/football/greece-vs-belgium/report/350170 |archive-date=4 September 2017}}</ref> At the World Cup, Belgium won all their [[2018 FIFA World Cup Group G|group]] matches, against [[Panama national football team|Panama]], [[Tunisia national football team|Tunisia]] and [[England national football team|England]], progressing to the knockout stage as group winners.<ref>{{cite web |date=28 June 2018 |title=België verslaat Engeland en gaat als groepswinnaar verder op WK |trans-title=Belgium beats England to advance to World Cup as group winners |url=https://www.nu.nl/wk-2018/5337296/belgie-verslaat-engeland-en-gaat-als-groepswinnaar-verder-wk.html?referrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com%2F |access-date= |work=nu.nl/wk-2018 |language=nl}}</ref> In the [[2018 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#Round of 16|round of 16]] they trailed 2–0 against [[Japan national football team|Japan]], but eventually won 3–2 with a 94th minute winner by [[Nacer Chadli]].<ref>{{cite web |date=28 October 2022 |title=Nacer Chadli Goal 90'+4' &#124; Belgium v Japan &#124; 2018 FIFA World Cup Russia |url=https://www.plus.fifa.com/en/content/nacer-chadli-goal-904-belgium-v-japan-2018-fifa-world-cup-russia/6436070c-fa4e-4267-9ed4-a3048649d038?gl=be |access-date= |work=plus.fifa.com |language=}}</ref> The Red Devils defeated Brazil 2–1 in the [[2018 FIFA World Cup#Quarter-finals|quarter-finals]],<ref>{{cite web |date=6 July 2018 |title=Brazil v Belgium &#124; Quarter-finals &#124; 2018 FIFA World Cup Russia &#124; Extended Highlights |url=https://www.plus.fifa.com/en/content/belgium-v-brazil-quarter-finals-2018-fifa-world-cup-extended-highlights/978454d9-88f5-42ce-ba68-5e4757ee4242?gl=be |access-date= |work=plus.fifa.com |language=}}</ref> and would be eliminated in the [[2018 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#Semi-finals|semi-finals]] by eventual champions France. They eventually won the third place play-off against England.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=Scott |last2=Andrews |first2=Kendra |last3=Flaherty |first3=Bryan |date=14 July 2018 |title=Belgium claims third place at World Cup with a 2–0 win over England |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/soccer-insider/wp/2018/07/14/belgium-vs-england-2018-world-cup-third-place-playoff/?noredirect=on |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=15 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200920062217/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/soccer-insider/wp/2018/07/14/belgium-vs-england-2018-world-cup-third-place-playoff/?noredirect=on |archive-date=20 September 2020 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On 16 November 2019, for the first time in its history the team topped the [[World Football Elo Ratings]], after a 1–4 away win over Russia during the [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying|Euro 2020 qualifiers]].<ref name="World Football Elo Ratings" />

Being considered one of the biggest contenders for the [[UEFA Euro 2020|European trophy]], the tournament was a complete disappointment for Belgium. Being drawn in Group B alongside Russia, [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] and [[Finland national football team|Finland]], Belgium easily conquered the group with three wins.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51197540|title=Belgium's Lukaku in goal tribute to Eriksen|work=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/19692/12335073/denmark-1-2-belgium-kevin-de-bruyne-inspires-red-devils-to-victory-as-they-reach-last-16|title=Denmark 1-2 Belgium: Kevin De Bruyne inspires Red Devils to victory as they reach Euro 2020 last 16|website=Sky Sports}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/sports/football/euro-2020-live-score-finland-vs-belgium-can-kevin-de-bruyne-inspire-belgium-to-undefeated-run-in-group-b-101624280380073.html|title=Euro 2020 Highlights, Finland vs Belgium: Belgium beat Finland 2-0, finish at top position in Group B|date=21 June 2021|website=Hindustan Times}}</ref> In the [[UEFA Euro 2020 knockout stage|knockout phase]], Belgium faced reigning champions [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] in the round of 16 with a strike from [[Thorgan Hazard]] to give Belgium a 1–0 win.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/euro-2020/belgium-beat-reigning-champions-portugal-1-0-in-euro-2020/2287251|title=Belgium beat reigning champions Portugal 1-0 in Euro 2020|website=www.aa.com.tr}}</ref> In the quarter-finals, Belgium faced Italy, failing to take revenge for their 2016 loss, suffering a 1–2 defeat, with the goal being scored by [[Romelu Lukaku]], ending Belgium's campaign on a sad note.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51198657|title=Italy edge Belgium to set up Spain semi|work=BBC Sport }}</ref>

At the [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022 World Cup]] in [[Qatar]], Belgium were drawn into [[2022 FIFA World Cup Group F|Group F]] alongside [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]], [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]] and [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]]. Despite starting their campaign well with a 1–0 victory over Canada, they suffered a shock 2–0 defeat to Morocco, and following a 0–0 draw with Croatia in their final group game, Belgium were knocked out of the tournament at the group stage for the first time since [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Belgium knocked out of World Cup after goalless draw with Croatia as head coach Roberto Martinez steps down|url=https://www.cnn.com/2022/12/01/football/belgium-croatia-group-f-world-cup-spt-intl|website=[[CNN]]|date=1 December 2022}}</ref> Following their elimination from the tournament, Martínez announced that he would be standing down as head coach after six years in charge of the national team.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Roberto Martínez Stands Down As Belgium Manager After World Cup Exit |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/world-cup/roberto-martinez-belgium-manager-croatia-b2237182.html?amp |website=The Independent |date=1 December 2022 }}</ref>

In February 2023, it was announced that [[Domenico Tedesco]] has been appointed as the new head coach of the Belgian national team, replacing Roberto Martinez on a contract lasting until the end of [[UEFA Euro 2024|Euro 2024]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=Tedesco appointed as Belgium boss |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/64566792 |access-date=8 February 2023}}</ref> At the finals, Belgium were eliminated in the [[UEFA Euro 2024 knockout stage|round of 16]], losing 1–0 to France.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/c25ln8kzdndt |title=France 1–0 Belgium |first=Gary |last=Rose |website=BBC Sport |date=1 July 2024 |access-date=4 July 2024}}</ref>

