}}

In home matches, the team's [[Glossary of association football terms#O|outfield player]]s traditionally wear the colours of the [[Flag of Belgium|Belgian flag]]: black, yellow and red.<ref>{{cite web |title=Belgium |url=https://flagspot.net/flags/be.html |publisher=[[Flags of the World (website)|Flags of the World]] |date=6 June 2009 |access-date=3 October 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200920062449/https://www.fotw.info/flags/be.html |archive-date=20 September 2020}}</ref><ref name="HistFK1">{{cite web |title=fifa world cup 1930 group 4 |publisher=Historical Football Kits |url=http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/international/tournaments/fifa-world-cup/1930/1930-group-d.html |access-date=10 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408224335/http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/international/tournaments/fifa-world-cup/1930/1930-group-d.html |archive-date=8 April 2016}}</ref><ref name="GOAAAL80"/> Red dominates the strip and is often the sole jersey colour.<ref name="HistFK1"/><ref name="GOAAAL80"/> The away colours are usually white, black or both;<ref name="GOAAAL">{{cite web |url=http://goaaal.arch.be/index.php?l=nl&page=1920 |title=Goaaal! Fotomontage Rode Duivels |trans-title=Goaaal! Photo gallery Red Devils |language=nl |publisher=[[State Archives in Belgium|Belgian State Archives]] |access-date=20 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626095319/http://goaaal.arch.be/index.php?l=nl&page=1920 |archive-date=26 June 2016}}</ref> in 2014, the squad introduced a third, yellow kit.<ref name="WC2014shirts">{{cite news |title=Met deze shirts spelen Rode Duivels op het WK |trans-title=Red Devils play at the WC in these shirts |first=Maarten |last=Delvaux |language=nl |newspaper=[[De Standaard]] |url=http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20140227_019 |date=27 February 2014 |access-date=3 May 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626095414/http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20140227_019 |archive-date=26 June 2016}}</ref> Their shirts are often trimmed with ''tricolores'' at the margins.<ref name="GOAAAL80">{{cite web |url=http://goaaal.arch.be/index.php?l=nl&page=1980 |title=Goaaal! Fotomontage Rode Duivels – 1980 |trans-title=Goaaal! Photo gallery Red Devils – 1980 |language=nl |publisher=[[State Archives in Belgium|Belgian State Archives]] |access-date=20 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626095623/http://goaaal.arch.be/index.php?l=nl&page=1980 |archive-date=26 June 2016}}</ref><ref name="GOAAAL70" >{{cite web |url=http://goaaal.arch.be/index.php?l=nl&page=1970 |title=Goaaal! Fotomontage Rode Duivels – 1970 |trans-title=Goaaal! Photo gallery Red Devils – 1970 |language=nl |publisher=[[State Archives in Belgium|Belgian State Archives]] |access-date=20 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626095520/http://goaaal.arch.be/index.php?l=nl&page=1970 |archive-date=26 June 2016}}</ref> Since 1981, the RBFA emblem has been the national team's badge;<ref name="GOAAAL80"/><ref name="fotocoll81">{{cite web |title=Voetbal: Nederland- België 3–0 |trans-title=Football: The Netherlands-Belgium 3–0 |url=http://www.gahetna.nl/collectie/afbeeldingen/fotocollectie/zoeken/weergave/detail/start/0/tstart/0/q/zoekterm/belgi%C3%AB%20voetbal%201981 |language=nl |publisher=gahetNA (Genootschap voor het Nationaal Archief, het [[Nationaal Archief]], [[Spaarnestad Photo]])|access-date=7 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626095711/http://www.gahetna.nl/collectie/afbeeldingen/fotocollectie/zoeken/weergave/detail/start/0/tstart/0/q/zoekterm/belgi%C3%AB%20voetbal%201981 |archive-date=26 June 2016}}</ref> the previous badge was a yellow lion on a black shield,<ref name="HistFK1"/><ref name="GOAAAL80"/> similar to the escutcheon of the [[Coat of arms of Belgium|national coat of arms]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.belgium.be/en/about_belgium/country/belgium_in_nutshell/symbols/coats_of_arms/ |title=Heraldic emblem and motto |publisher=[[Federal Government of Belgium|Belgian Federal Government]] |access-date=31 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200920062634/https://www.belgium.be/en/about_belgium/country/belgium_in_nutshell/symbols/coats_of_arms |archive-date=20 September 2020}}</ref> On 8 November 2019, the [[Royal Belgian Football Association]] revealed a new logo, which preserved the main elements of the previous one: the royal crown, the [[wreath]] and the Belgian tricolor.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.footyheadlines.com/2019/06/all-new-belgium-logo.html |title=All-New Belgium Logo Revealed – 2020 Kit Debut Imminent |date=8 November 2019 |website=Footy Headlines |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200726185533/https://www.footyheadlines.com/2019/06/all-new-belgium-logo.html |archive-date=26 July 2020 |access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref>

For their first unofficial match in 1901, the Belgian team wore white jerseys with tricoloured bands on the upper arms.{{sfn|Fraiponts|Willocx|2003}} Around their third unofficial match in 1902, the choice was made for a "shirt with national colours&nbsp;... [that would indicate,] with a stripe, the number of times every player has participated in an encounter".{{sfn|Hubert|1980|p=12}} Since 1904, Belgium's classic all-red jersey design has been altered twice. In 1904–05, the squad briefly wore satin shirts with three horizontal bands in red, yellow and black; according to sports journalist [[Victor Boin]], the shirts set "the ugliness record".{{sfn|Boin|1945}} During the 1970s, manager Raymond Goethals chose an all-white combination to improve the team's visibility during evening matches.<ref name="WhiteDevil">{{cite news |url=http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dst23052002_100 |title=WK-geschiedenis. 1970. Witte Duivels smelten weg in Mexico |trans-title=WC history. 1970. White Devils melt away in Mexico |newspaper=[[De Standaard]] |first=Bart |last=Lagae |language=nl |date=23 May 2002 |access-date=26 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626095901/http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dst23052002_100 |archive-date=26 June 2016}}</ref><ref name="bruzzz"/>

Six clothing manufacturers have supplied the official team strip. [[Adidas]] is the producer since 2014,<ref>{{cite news |title=New Adidas Belgium 2014–15 Kits Released |publisher=Footy Headlines |url=http://www.footyheadlines.com/2014/08/new-adidas-belgium-2014-15-kits.html |date=14 August 2014 |access-date=3 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626095944/http://www.footyheadlines.com/2014/08/new-adidas-belgium-2014-15-kits.html |archive-date=26 June 2016}}</ref> and closed a sponsorship deal with the RBFA until 2026;<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sporza.be/nl/2020/09/02/adidas-is-nog-minstens-6-jaar-kledingsponsor-van-de-rode-duivels~1599035462930/ |title=Adidas is nog minstens 6 jaar kledingsponsor van de Rode Duivels |trans-title=Adidas remains the clothing sponsor of the Red Devils for at least 6 years |language=nl |access-date=2 September 2020 |publisher=[[Sporza]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200920063334/https://sporza.be/nl/2020/09/02/adidas-is-nog-minstens-6-jaar-kledingsponsor-van-de-rode-duivels~1599035462930/ |archive-date=20 September 2020 |url-status=dead }}</ref> it was also the supplier from 1974 to 1980, and from 1983 to 1991.<ref name="sponsortimeline"/> Former kit manufacturers are [[Umbro]] (early 1970s),<ref name="bruzzz">{{cite web |url=http://www.bruzz.be/nl/nieuws/rode-duivels-witte-engelen |title=Rode Duivels, witte engelen |trans-title=Red Devils, white angels |language=nl |publisher=BRUZZZ |date=5 June 2014 |access-date=17 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160721103441/http://www.bruzz.be/nl/nieuws/rode-duivels-witte-engelen |archive-date=21 July 2016}}</ref><ref name="sponsortimeline"/> [[Admiral Sportswear|Admiral]] (1981–1982),{{efn|Belgium played in an Adidas outfit in their last match of 1980, against Cyprus on 21 December.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.video.sporza.be/cm/sporza.mobile.video/1.2283869 |title=1980: België klopt Cyprus met 0–2 |trans-title=1980: Belgium beats Cyprus 0–2 |language=nl |access-date=28 October 2016 |publisher=[[Sporza]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161029044616/http://m.video.sporza.be/cm/sporza.mobile.video/1.2283869 |archive-date=29 October 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> This suggests that Admiral's sponsorship started in 1981, contrary to what the 2014 article stated.}}<ref name="sponsortimeline">{{cite news |title=Adidas na WK wellicht nieuwe kledingsponsor Duivels |trans-title=Adidas likely new Devils clothing sponsor after WC |newspaper=[[Het Nieuwsblad]] |first=Ludo |last=Vandewalle |language=nl |date=24 May 2014 |access-date=9 May 2015 |url=http://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20140523_01117328 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626100118/http://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20140523_01117328 |archive-date=26 June 2016}}</ref> [[Diadora]] (1992–1998),<ref name="sponsortimeline"/> [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] (1999–2009) and Burrda (2010–2014).{{efn|The timeline in the 2015 overview article stated the switch from Diadora to Nike happened in 1998. However, the 1999 article focused on this kit sponsor change which took place in mid-1999.}}<ref name="sponsortimeline"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Rode Duivels in "rood, klassiek en rustig" shirt |trans-title=Red Devils in "red, classic and serene" shirt |newspaper=[[De Standaard]] |first=Sander |last=Van den Broecke |language=nl |date=1 July 1999 |access-date=8 July 2013 |url=http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dst9907010068 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112173027/http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dst9907010068 |archive-date=12 November 2013}}</ref>
