===Media coverage===
[[File:Gust De Muynck Belgium-Netherlands 1931.jpg|thumb|260px|upright=1.2|Gust De Muynck's live coverage during Belgium–Netherlands in 1931|alt=Journalist, seated in the stands and speaking into a microphone]]
The first live coverage of a Belgian sporting event occurred on 3 May 1931, when journalist [[Gust De Muynck]] commentated on the football match between Belgium and the Netherlands on radio.<ref>{{cite news |title=Archiefmeester: Radio & voetbal |trans-title=Archive master: Radio & football |publisher=[[Radio 1 (Belgium)|Radio 1]] |language=nl |date=16 March 2014 |access-date=13 April 2014 |url=http://old.radio1.be/programmas/nele-radioland/archiefmeester-radio-voetbal-0 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628194728/http://old.radio1.be/programmas/nele-radioland/archiefmeester-radio-voetbal-0 |archive-date=28 June 2016}}</ref> Later, football broadcasts were also televised. As 60 per cent of Belgians speak [[Dutch language|Dutch]] and 40 per cent speak [[French language|French]],<ref name="CIA-Bel">{{cite web |title=The World Factbook – Europe – Belgium |publisher=[[Central Intelligence Agency]] |date=30 June 2016 |access-date=10 July 2016 |url=https://www.cia.gov/the-world-factbook/countries/belgium/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210109104644/https://www.cia.gov/the-world-factbook/countries/belgium |url-status=dead |archive-date=9 January 2021 }}</ref> commentaries for the national team matches are provided in both languages. The matches are not broadcast in [[German language|German]]—Belgium's third official language.<ref name="CIA-Bel"/> During Belgium's tournament appearances in the 1980s and the early 1990s, [[Rik De Saedeleer]] crowned himself the nation's most famous football commentator with his emotional and humorous reports.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rik, de dertiende man van de Rode Duivels |trans-title=Rik, the thirteenth man of the Red Devils |newspaper=[[Het Laatste Nieuws]] |language=nl |first=Joeri |last=Vlemings |date=5 March 2013 |access-date=29 May 2014 |url=http://www.hln.be/hln/nl/944/Celebrities/article/detail/1590983/2013/03/05/Rik-de-dertiende-man-van-de-Rode-Duivels.dhtml |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628194835/http://www.hln.be/hln/nl/944/Celebrities/article/detail/1590983/2013/03/05/Rik-de-dertiende-man-van-de-Rode-Duivels.dhtml |archive-date=28 June 2016}}</ref>

Initially the matches were transmitted mainly on public television channels: the former BRTN (now [[Vlaamse Radio- en Televisieomroeporganisatie|VRT]]) in Dutch, and the [[RTBF]] in French. Since 1994, commercial channels such as [[VTM (TV channel)|vtm]] and its sister channel [[VTM 2|Kanaal 2]], and [[Play4 (TV channel)|VIER]] in [[Flanders]], have purchased broadcasting rights.<ref name="RBFAhist">{{cite web |title=The RBFA's History |publisher=[[Royal Belgian Football Association|RBFA]] |access-date=9 May 2014 |url=http://www.belgianfootball.be/en/rbfas-history |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628194935/http://www.belgianfootball.be/en/rbfas-history |archive-date=28 June 2016}}</ref> The Euro 2016 [[UEFA Euro 2016 knockout phase#Hungary vs Belgium|round of 16 match against Hungary]] was the most-watched programme in Belgian television history, with an audience of over 4 million viewers out of 11.3 million Belgians.<ref name="CIA-Bel"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Opnieuw gigantisch hoge kijkcijfers voor wedstrijd van Rode Duivels |trans-title=Again high viewer numbers for Red Devils match |newspaper=[[Het Nieuwsblad]] |language=nl |date=27 June 2016 |access-date=27 August 2016 |url=http://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20160627_02358622 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827095206/http://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20160627_02358622 |archive-date=27 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Kijkcijferrecord EK Rode Duivels verbroken |trans-title=Viewer record Red Devils' EC broken |publisher=[[Vlaamse Radio- en Televisieomroeporganisatie|VRT]] |language=nl |date=1 August 2016 |access-date=27 August 2016 |url=http://www.vrt.be/nieuws/2016/08/kijkcijferrecord-ek-rode-duivels-verbroken |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827095249/http://www.vrt.be/nieuws/2016/08/kijkcijferrecord-ek-rode-duivels-verbroken |archive-date=27 August 2016}}</ref>

In April 2014, the VRT started transmitting a nine-piece, behind-the-scenes documentary about the national team filmed during the 2014 World Cup qualifiers, titled ''Iedereen Duivel'' (''Everybody Devil'').<ref>{{cite news |title=Nieuwe Vrt-reeks kijkt mee achter de schermen van de Rode Duivels |trans-title=New Vrt series watches behind the scenes of the Red Devils |newspaper=[[De Standaard]] |language=nl |date=3 April 2014|access-date=3 April 2014 |url=http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20140403_01053428 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628195157/http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20140403_01053428 |archive-date=28 June 2016}}</ref> Cable broadband provider [[Telenet (provider)|Telenet]] broadcast an eight-part documentary about individual players titled ''Rode Helden'' (''Red Heroes'').<ref>{{cite news |title=Docureeks 'Rode Helden' op Sporting Telenet |trans-title=Documentary series 'Red Heroes' on Sporting Telenet |publisher=[[Telenet (Belgium)|Telenet]] |language=nl |date=25 April 2014 |access-date=17 May 2014 |url=http://corporate.telenet.be/nl/nieuws-en-media/persberichten/docureeks-rode-helden-op-sporting-telenet |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200920064501/https://press.telenet.be/docureeks-rode-helden-op-sporting-telenet |archive-date=20 September 2020}}</ref>

===Side activities===
[[File:France-Belgium 1918-04-21.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Illustration of Belgium's game against France in April 1918: some of such unofficial wartime matches served as charity fundraisers.|alt=Old cartoon of an association football match with the goalkeeper in the middle who jumps and hits the ball]]
Multiple events were organised for the fans during the squad's peak popularity in the 2010s. During the 2014 World Cup qualifiers, a string of interactive events called the ''Devil Challenges'' were organised.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Challenges |newspaper=IAB Community |url=http://www.iab-community.be/cases/the-challenges-de-duiveluitdagingen-les-dzfis-des-diables/ |access-date=7 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628195326/http://www.iab-community.be/cases/the-challenges-de-duiveluitdagingen-les-dzfis-des-diables/ |archive-date=28 June 2016}}</ref> The premise was that small groups of international players would do a favour in return for each of the five comprehensive chores their supporters completed ("colour Belgium red", "gather 500,000 [[decibel]]s", etc.), all of which were accomplished.<ref>{{cite news |title=Duiveluitdagingen stuwen Duivels naar Brazilië |trans-title=Devil Challenges push Devils to Brazil |newspaper=[[Sporza]] |language=nl |date=15 October 2013 |access-date=5 May 2015 |url=http://sporza.be/cm/sporza/extra/deduiveluitdagingen/1.1754902 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628195430/http://sporza.be/cm/sporza/extra/deduiveluitdagingen/1.1754902 |archive-date=28 June 2016}}</ref> In June 2013, the Belgian national team's first ever Fan Day attracted over 20,000 supporters;<ref name="HLN020613">{{cite news |title=Groot succes: 20.000 fans op eerste fandag Rode Duivels |trans-title=Great success: 20,000 fans on first fan day Red Devils |newspaper=[[Het Laatste Nieuws]] |language=nl |date=2 June 2013 |access-date=30 June 2013 |url=http://www.hln.be/hln/nl/16076/De-Rode-Duivels/article/detail/1644543/2013/06/02/Groot-succes-20-000-fans-op-eerste-fandag-Rode-Duivels.dhtml |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628195538/http://www.hln.be/hln/nl/16076/De-Rode-Duivels/article/detail/1644543/2013/06/02/Groot-succes-20-000-fans-op-eerste-fandag-Rode-Duivels.dhtml |archive-date=28 June 2016}}</ref> a second was held after the 2014 World Cup.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rode Duivels bedanken 'beste supporters ter wereld' met fandag |trans-title=Red Devils thank 'best supporters in the world' with fan day |first1=Kim |last1=De Raedt |first2=Lin |last2=Louage |newspaper=[[De Standaard]] |language=nl |date=6 July 2014 |access-date=6 July 2014 |url=http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20140706_01168643 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628195633/http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20140706_01168643 |archive-date=28 June 2016}}</ref> On the days of Belgium's 2014 World Cup group matches, large dance events titled ''Dance with the Devils'' took place in three Belgian cities.<ref>{{cite news |title=Dance with the Devils op 17, 22 en 26 juni |trans-title=Dance with the Devils on 17, 22 and 26 June |publisher=[[Sportpaleis]] |language=nl |date=14 February 2014 |access-date=5 May 2015 |url=https://www.sportpaleis.be/nl/news/view/2014-02-14/dance_with_the_devils_op_17_22_en_26_juni |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140811161753/http://www.sportpaleis.be/nl/news/view/2014-02-14/dance_with_the_devils_op_17_22_en_26_juni |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 August 2014}}</ref> This activity was repeated during Belgium's Euro 2016 group matches.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lotto-arena.be/nl/kalender/2016-2017/dance-with-the-devils |title=Dance With The Devils |language=nl |publisher= [[Lotto Arena]] |access-date=9 June 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628195831/http://www.lotto-arena.be/nl/kalender/2016-2017/dance-with-the-devils |archive-date=28 June 2016}}</ref>

Occasionally, the Belgian team directly supported charity. Between 1914 and 1941 they played at least five unofficial matches of which the returns were for charitable purposes: two against France,<ref name="DT210316"/><ref name="FraBelWWIa">{{cite news |url=http://www.delpher.nl/nl/kranten/view?coll=ddd&identifier=MMSAEN01%3A000044842%3Ampeg21%3Aa0027 |newspaper=Twentsch dagblad Tubantia |via=[[Delpher]] |title=Frankrijk–België (0–1) |trans-title=France–Belgium (0–1) |language=nl |date=21 December 1914 |access-date=23 July 2016}}</ref> and three against the Netherlands.<ref name="DerbyBelNed"/><ref name="BelNed1941">{{cite news |url=http://www.delpher.nl/nl/kranten/view?coll=ddd&identifier=ddd%3A011221616%3Ampeg21%3Aa0104 |newspaper=[[Bataviaasch Nieuwsblad]] |via=[[Delpher]] |title=Rond den Wedstrijd Holland – België |trans-title=About the game Holland – Belgium |language=nl |date=3 February 1941 |access-date=11 June 2015}}</ref> In 1986, when the Belgian delegation reached the World Cup semi-finals, the squad started a project titled Casa Hogar, an idea of delegation leader [[Michel D'Hooghe]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://wvw.nacion.com/ln_ee/1998/junio/22/deportes17.html |title=Bélgica en el alma |trans-title=Belgium in the soul |language=es |newspaper=[[La Nación (San José)|La Nación]] |first=Adolfo |last=Garza |date=22 June 1998 |access-date=30 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151121083620/http://wvw.nacion.com/ln_ee/1998/junio/22/deportes17.html |archive-date=21 November 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Casa Hogar is a home for street children in the Mexican industrial city of [[Toluca]], to which the footballers donated part of their tournament bonuses.<ref>{{cite news |title=Retro. Ceulemans: 'Voor mij blijft EK 80 het hoogtepunt' |trans-title=Retro. Ceulemans: 'EC 80 is still the summit for me' |newspaper=[[Het Nieuwsblad]] |first=François |last=Colin |language=nl |date=10 June 2011 |access-date=21 November 2015 |url=https://www.nieuwsblad.be/sportwereld/cnt/9e3b7f4r |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200924204941/https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/9e3b7f4r |archive-date=24 September 2020}}</ref> In August 2013, the national team supported four social projects through the charity fund Football+ Foundation, by playing an A-match with a plus sign on the shoulders of their jerseys and auctioning the shirts.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bied op de wedstrijdshirts van België-Frankrijk |trans-title=Place a bid on the match shirts of Belgium-France |publisher=[[RBFA]] |language=nl |date=8 August 2013 |access-date=15 August 2013 |url=http://www.belgianfootball.be/nl/nieuws/bied-op-de-wedstrijdshirts-van-belgi%C3%AB-frankrijk |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628200104/http://www.belgianfootball.be/nl/nieuws/bied-op-de-wedstrijdshirts-van-belgi%C3%AB-frankrijk |archive-date=28 June 2016}}</ref>

In the 21st century, several national team players acted up against discrimination. In 2002, the national squad held its first anti-[[Racism in association football|racism]] campaign in which they posed with slogans.<ref>{{cite web |title=Goaaal! Voetbalaffiches |trans-title=Goaaal! Football posters |language=nl |url=http://goaaal.arch.be/index.php?l=nl&page=affiches |publisher=[[RBFA]] |access-date=14 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628200238/http://goaaal.arch.be/index.php?l=nl&page=affiches |archive-date=28 June 2016}}</ref> A home Euro 2012 qualifier was given the theme of respect for [[cultural diversity|diversity]] in 2010; this UEFA-supported action was part of the European [[Fare network|FARE]] Action Week.<ref>{{cite news |title=European Action Week against discrimination in football to kick off next week |date=8 October 2010 |access-date=27 July 2013 |url=http://fairplay.vidc.org/en/fairplay-news/single-view/article/die-europaeische-fare-aktionswoche-gegen-diskriminierung-im-fussball-wird-naechste-woche-angepfiffen/ |publisher=Vienna Institute for International Dialogue and Cooperation |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628200322/http://fairplay.vidc.org/en/fairplay-news/single-view/article/die-europaeische-fare-aktionswoche-gegen-diskriminierung-im-fussball-wird-naechste-woche-angepfiffen/ |archive-date=28 June 2016}}</ref> Ex-Red Devil [[Dimitri Mbuyu]]—the first black Belgium player (in 1987)<ref name="AllRedD">{{cite web |url=https://www.rbfa.be/en/national-teams/red-devils/all-red-devils |publisher=[[RBFA]] |title=All Red Devils |access-date=8 May 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=http://sportmagazine.knack.be/sport/voetbal-nationaal/mununga-ik-was-te-naief/article-normal-162603.html |journal=Sport/Voetbalmagazine |publisher=[[Roularta Media Group]] |location=Roeselare |first=Pierre |last=Danvoye |language=nl |title=Mununga: 'Ik was te naïef' |trans-title=Mununga: 'I was too naive' |date=2 July 2013 |access-date=14 August 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628200605/http://sportmagazine.knack.be/sport/voetbal-nationaal/mununga-ik-was-te-naief/article-normal-162603.html |archive-date=28 June 2016}}</ref>—was engaged as godfather, and other foreign, current, and former footballers who played in the [[Belgian Pro League|Belgian top division]] participated.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.rtbf.be/sport/football/detail_les-diables-contre-le-racisme?id=3745713 |title=Les Diables contre le racisme |trans-title=The Devils against racism |publisher=[[RTBF]] |language=fr |date=11 October 2010 |access-date=24 October 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628200714/http://www.rtbf.be/sport/football/detail_les-diables-contre-le-racisme?id=3745713 |archive-date=28 June 2016}}</ref> In 2018, four national team players spoke up against [[Violence against LGBT people|homophobic violence]], in a video clip made by organisation [[Kick It Out (organisation)|Kick It Out]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20180227_03380486 |title=Rode Duivels strijden mee tegen homofoob geweld |trans-title=Red Devils join the fight against homophobic violence |language=nl |newspaper=[[De Standaard]] |author=vva |date=27 February 2018 |access-date=3 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227183153/http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20180227_03380486 |archive-date=27 February 2018 }}</ref>

===Nickname, logo and mascot===
[[File:OO-SNA_Airbus_A320-214_-_BEL_"Belgian_Red_Devils"_(27254966721).jpg|thumb|260px|"Belgian Red Devils" airbus with trident logo, pictured in 2016]]
After a 1905 match, a Dutch reporter wrote that three Belgian footballers "work[ed] as devils".<ref name="RN160505">{{cite news |url=http://www.delpher.nl/nl/kranten/view?coll=ddd&identifier=ddd:010213644:mpeg21:p006 |newspaper=[[Algemeen Dagblad|Rotterdamsch Nieuwsblad]] |via=[[Delpher]] |title=Den wedstrijd om den Rotterdamsch Nieuwsblad-Beker |trans-title=The match for the Rotterdamsch Nieuwsblad Cup |language=nl |date=16 May 1905 |access-date=17 May 2015}}</ref> A year later [[Léopold FC]] manager Pierre Walckiers nicknamed the players Red Devils, inspired by their jersey colour, and the achievement of three successive victories in 1906.{{sfn|Guldemont|Deps|1995|p=65}}<ref name="results" /> Because of their white home shirts in the 1970s, they were temporarily known as the White Devils.<ref name="WhiteDevil" /> Since 2012, the team logo is a red trident (or three-pronged pitchfork),<ref>{{cite news |title=Bob Madou doet duivelse marketingstrategie uit de doeken |trans-title=Bob Madou reveals devilish marketing strategy |publisher=voka.be |language=nl |date=17 May 2016 |url=https://www.voka.be/limburg/nieuws/2016/5/bob-madou-doet-duivelse-marketingstrategie-uit-de-doeken/ |access-date=28 June 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628203546/http://www.voka.be/limburg/nieuws/2016/5/bob-madou-doet-duivelse-marketingstrategie-uit-de-doeken/ |archive-date=28 June 2016}}</ref> an item that is often associated with the devil.{{sfn|Russell|1987|p=129}} Apart from that, the national squad has also had four official [[Anthropomorphism|anthropomorphous]] mascots. The first was a lion in team kit named Diabolix,<ref name="mascot" /> a reference to the central symbol in the Belgian coat of arms that appeared on the team jerseys from 1905 to 1980.<ref name="GOAAAL80" /><ref name="fotocoll1905">{{cite web |title=Fotocollectie – Evenals 74 jaar geleden speelt het Nederlands voetbalelftal a.s. woensdag tegen&nbsp;... |trans-title=Photo collection – Just like 74 years ago the Dutch eleven play upcoming Wednesday against&nbsp;... |url=https://www.gahetna.nl/collectie/afbeeldingen/fotocollectie/zoeken/weergave/detail/start/0/tstart/0/q/zoekterm/belgi%C3%AB%201905 |language=nl |publisher=gahetNA (Genootschap voor het Nationaal Archief, het [[Nationaal Archief]], [[Spaarnestad Photo]]) |access-date=17 July 2016}}</ref> In accordance with their epithet, the next mascots were a red super-devil and two fan-made modern devils; the one introduced in 2018 was named "Red".<ref name="mascot">{{cite news |title=Nieuwe mascotte voor Rode Duivels |trans-title=New mascot for Red Devils |author=mcu |newspaper=[[Het Nieuwsblad]] |language=nl |date=6 February 2007 |url=https://www.nieuwsblad.be/sportwereld/cnt/b367254070206 |access-date=3 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200924210421/https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/b367254070206 |archive-date=24 September 2020}}</ref><ref name="mascot2">{{cite news |title=VIDEO: Nieuwe mascotte Rode Duivels uitgebroed, het is een... rode duivel |trans-title=VIDEO: New mascot Red Devils hatched, it is a ... red devil |newspaper=[[Sporza]] |language=nl |date=14 March 2018 |url=http://archief.sporza.be/cm/sporza/voetbal/Rode_Duivels/1.3163364 |access-date=3 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180603084010/http://archief.sporza.be/cm/sporza/voetbal/Rode_Duivels/1.3163364 |archive-date=3 June 2018}}</ref> A trident logo, referring to a devil, is also used frequently.<ref>{{Cite web |date=12 November 2022 |title=THE TRIP OF OUR RED DEVILS |url=https://www.rbfa.be/en/news/trip-our-red-devils |website=rbfa.b |language=}}</ref>

===Supporters===
{{quote box |width=250px |bgcolor=#c6dbf7 |align=left |quote="Cycling is the traditional national sport of Belgium, but soccer is the most popular." |source=—Historian Richard Henshaw, 1979{{sfn|Henshaw|1979|p=75}}}}
Fans of the Belgian national team display the country's tricolour national flag, usually with an emphasis on the red element. In 2012, local supporter clubs merged into one large Belgian federation named "1895" after the foundation year of the RBFA. One year later, 1895 had 24,000 members.<ref>{{cite news |title=1895, een gigantisch succes |trans-title=1895, a gigantic success |language=nl |date=24 June 2013 |url=http://www.belgianfootball.be/nl/nieuws/1895-een-gigantisch-succes |publisher=[[RBFA]] |access-date=9 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628200800/http://www.belgianfootball.be/nl/nieuws/1895-een-gigantisch-succes |archive-date=28 June 2016}}</ref> The nationwide interest in the national team has also been reflected by the occasional presence of [[Monarchy of Belgium|Belgian monarch]]s at their matches since 1914.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.delpher.nl/nl/kranten/view?coll=ddd&identifier=ddd%3A010295448%3Ampeg21%3Aa0029 |title=Sport |trans-title=Sports |newspaper=[[Algemeen Dagblad|Rotterdamsch Nieuwsblad]] |via=[[Delpher]] |language=nl |date=26 February 1914 |access-date=8 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gva.be/cnt/aid1399751/ook-koning-albert-naar-de-heizel |title=Ook koning Albert vanavond naar de Heizel |trans-title=King Albert also at the Heysel this evening |language=nl |newspaper=[[Gazet van Antwerpen]] |first=F. |last=Vranckx |date=7 June 2013 |access-date=8 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628200853/http://www.gva.be/cnt/aid1399751/ook-koning-albert-naar-de-heizel |archive-date=28 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://sporza.be/cm/sporza/matchcenter/mc_voetbal/voorronde_EK_2016_rode_duivels/MG_groep_B_speeldag_7/1.2428852 |title=Rode Duivels staan op tegen Bosnië-Herzegovina |trans-title=Red Devils arise against Bosnia-Herzegovina |language=nl |publisher=[[Sporza]] |date=3 September 2015 |access-date=8 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628200944/http://sporza.be/cm/sporza/matchcenter/mc_voetbal/voorronde_EK_2016_rode_duivels/MG_groep_B_speeldag_7/1.2428852 |archive-date=28 June 2016}}</ref> One of the greatest moments for the Belgian team and their [[12th man (football)|12th man]] was in 1986 when the Belgian delegation at the World Cup received a warm "welcome home". When the World Cup semi-finalists appeared on the balcony of [[Brussels Town Hall]], the adjoining Grand Place square was filled with an ecstatic crowd that cheered as though their squad had won a major tournament.<ref>{{cite news |title=België trakteert zijn helden op een volksfeest |trans-title=Belgium treats its heroes with a national feast |language=nl |date=20 June 2011 |url=http://sporza.be/cm/sporza/voetbal/Rode_Duivels/1.1043863 |newspaper=[[Sporza]] |access-date=30 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628201044/http://sporza.be/cm/sporza/voetbal/Rode_Duivels/1.1043863 |archive-date=28 June 2016}}</ref>
[[File:ENG-BEL (12).jpg|260px|thumb|Crowd of Belgian fans in [[Kaliningrad Stadium]] at the 2018 World Cup|alt=Belgian fans wearing red at the 2018 World Cup in Kaliningrad]]
The team's deterioration after the 2002 World Cup led to their absence from the end stages of the next five major tournaments, and strained their popularity. Between 2004 and 2010, local journalists called the Belgian footballing nation "mortally ill".<ref>{{cite news |title=Ons voetballand is doodziek |trans-title=Our footballing nation is terminally ill |publisher=sport.be.msn.com |first=Bennie |last=Luyten |newspaper=Sport.be |language=nl |date=18 November 2004 |access-date=18 July 2013 |url=http://www.sport.be/nl/voetbal/rodeduivels/article.html?Article_ID=64879 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701153705/http://www.sport.be/nl/voetbal/rodeduivels/article.html?Article_ID=64879 |archive-date=1 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Advocaat laat Rode Duivels doodziek achter |trans-title=Advocaat leaves Red Devils terminally ill |website=belgiumsoccer.be |language=nl |date=15 April 2010 |access-date=18 July 2013 |url=http://www.belgiumsoccer.be/nieuws/lees/2010-04-15/advocaat-laat-rode-duivels-doodziek-achter |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112173232/http://www.belgiumsoccer.be/nieuws/lees/2010-04-15/advocaat-laat-rode-duivels-doodziek-achter |archive-date=12 November 2013}}</ref> Of the fans that kept supporting their squad in bad times, Ludo Rollenberg was one of the most loyal. He attended the team's matches worldwide since 1990, missing only the 1999 Japanese [[Kirin Cup Soccer|Kirin Cup]] and two other matches by 2006,<ref>{{cite news |title=De enige echte fan van België |trans-title=Belgium's only real fan |newspaper=[[Algemeen Dagblad]] |language=nl |date=5 October 2006 |access-date=30 June 2013 |url=http://www.ad.nl/ad/nl/1001/Sportwereld/article/detail/2331576/2006/10/05/De-enige-echte-fan-van-Belgie.dhtml |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628201355/http://www.ad.nl/ad/nl/1001/Sportwereld/article/detail/2331576/2006/10/05/De-enige-echte-fan-van-Belgie.dhtml |archive-date=28 June 2016}}</ref> and was the only supporter to attend their matches in Armenia in 2009.<ref>{{cite news |title=De eenzame Duivels-supporter |trans-title=The lonesome Devils supporter |newspaper=[[De Standaard]] |first=Ludo |last=Vandewalle |language=nl |date=9 September 2009 |access-date=30 June 2013 |url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/VH2ESCQ2 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200924210700/https://www.standaard.be/cnt/VH2ESCQ2 |archive-date=24 September 2020}}</ref>

Just before the kick-off of a 2014 World Cup home qualifier, Belgium's footballers saw a [[tifo]] banner, sized {{Convert|10.5 by 11.5|metres|feet}} depicting a devil in the national colours.<ref>{{cite news |title=De Rode Duivels zien vanavond hun eerste tifo |trans-title=The Red Devils see their first tifo tonight |publisher=[[Sporza]] |language=nl |date=6 June 2013 |access-date=4 July 2013 |url=https://sporza.be/nl/2013/06/06/de-rode-duivels-zien-vanavond-hun-eerste-tifo-1-1648955/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200924211121/https://sporza.be/nl/2013/06/06/de-rode-duivels-zien-vanavond-hun-eerste-tifo-1-1648955/ |archive-date=24 September 2020}}</ref> The presence of many Belgian players in top leagues abroad, such as the [[Premier League]],{{sfn|Willems|2013}} and promising results under Marc Wilmots, increased fans' enthusiasm and belief in a successful World Cup campaign.<ref name="HLN020613"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.voetbalnieuws.be/news/81443/Peiling:_Rode_Duivels_raken_tot_in_kwartfinales |title=Peiling: 'Rode Duivels raken tot in kwartfinales' |trans-title=Opinion poll: 'Red Devils reach the quarter finals' |language=nl |website=voetbalnieuws.be |date=17 October 2013 |access-date=22 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628201540/http://www.voetbalnieuws.be/news/81443/Peiling%3A_Rode_Duivels_raken_tot_in_kwartfinales |archive-date=28 June 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Because of this popularity, two Belgian monuments were decorated in national colours for the 2014 FIFA World Cup; the [[Manneken Pis]] statue received a child-sized version of the new Belgian uniform,<ref>{{cite news |title=Manneken Pis in WK-shirt Rode Duivels |trans-title=Manneken Pis in Red Devils WC shirt |language=nl |newspaper=[[De Standaard]] |url=http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20140307_01013684 |date=7 March 2014 |access-date=22 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628201644/http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20140307_01013684 |archive-date=28 June 2016}}</ref> and facets of the [[Atomium]]'s upper sphere were covered in black, yellow and red vinyl.<ref>{{cite news |title=Atomium-bol in zwart, geel en rood |trans-title=Atomium sphere in black, yellow and red |first=Lin |last=Louage |newspaper=[[De Standaard]] |language=nl |date=13 June 2014 |access-date=14 June 2014 |url=http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20140613_01139183 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160628201835/http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20140613_01139183 |archive-date=28 June 2016}}</ref>

===Rivalries===
{{See also|Low Countries derby}}
[[File:1905RNBmoment(2).jpg|thumb|260px|right|upright=1.3|Illustration of a Netherlands–Belgium cup match at Rotterdam's Schuttersveld pitch in 1905|alt=Match phase with two outfield players from each side]]
Belgium's main football rivals are its neighbors [[Netherlands national football team|the Netherlands]] and [[France national football team|France]], with which it shares close cultural and political relations.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.government.nl/topics/international-relations/contents/belgium |title=Relations to the Netherlands – Belgium |publisher=[[Politics of the Netherlands|Government of the Netherlands]] |access-date=20 August 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.diplomatie.gouv.fr/fr/dossiers-pays/belgique/la-france-et-la-belgique/ |title=La France et la Belgique |trans-title=France and Belgium |publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs and International Development (France)|France Diplomatie]] |language=fr |access-date=22 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629063055/http://www.diplomatie.gouv.fr/fr/dossiers-pays/belgique/la-france-et-la-belgique/ |archive-date=29 June 2016}}</ref>

====Netherlands====
The matchup between the Belgian and [[Netherlands national football team|Dutch team]] is known as the Low Countries [[Glossary of association football terms#D|derby]], {{as of|2025|09|lc=y}} they have played each other in 129 official matches.<ref name="DerbyBelNed"/> Belgium won the first four—unofficial—matches against the Netherlands,{{sfn|Hubert|1980|p=12}} but lost their first FIFA-recognised contest.<ref name="results"/> The two national teams played each other biannually between 1905 and 1964, except during the World Wars.<ref name="results"/> They have met 18 times in major tournaments, and have played at least [[Low Countries derby#Belgium vs. Netherlands Cups|35 friendly cup matches]]: in Belgium for the ''Coupe Vanden Abeele'', and in the Netherlands for the ''Rotterdamsch Nieuwsblad-Beker''.<ref name="TrouwCVA"/><ref name="RN160505"/> The overall balance favours the Netherlands, with 57 wins against 41 Belgian victories.<ref name="DerbyBelNed"/> The Low Countries' squads co-operated in fundraising initiatives between 1925 and 1941; they played seven unofficial matches for charity, FIFA and the Belgian Olympic Committee.<ref name="DerbyBelNed">{{cite web |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tablesb/belnedres.html |title=The "Derby der Lage Landen" |first=Karel |last=Stokkermans |date=21 September 2024 |access-date=1 December 2025 |website=[[RSSSF]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250902041043/https://www.rsssf.org/tablesb/belnedres.html |archive-date=2 September 2025}}</ref><ref name="BelNed1941"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.delpher.nl/nl/kranten/view?coll=ddd&identifier=ddd:011109369:mpeg21:a0205 |title=De extra België-Holland-wedstrijd. |trans-title=The extra Belgium-Holland game. |newspaper=[[Soerabaijasch Handelsblad]] |via=[[Delpher]] |date=26 April 1932 |access-date=25 May 2015 |language=nl}}</ref>

====France====
The clash between Belgium and France is nicknamed ''le Match Sympathique'' in French ("the Friendly Match");<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nrc.nl/handelsblad/1999/12/11/de-rode-duivels-7474159 |title=De Rode Duivels |trans-title=The Red Devils |language=nl |newspaper=[[NRC Handelsblad]] |first=Guus |last=Van Holland |date=11 December 1999 |access-date=20 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629063150/http://www.nrc.nl/handelsblad/1999/12/11/de-rode-duivels-7474159 |archive-date=29 June 2016}}</ref> they have contested 78 official matches {{as of|2025|09|lc=y}}.<ref name="belfrares">{{cite web |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tablesb/belfrares.html |title="Le match sympathique" |publisher=[[RSSSF]] |access-date=9 October 2025}}</ref> The first match between Belgium and France, the ''Évence Coppée'' Trophy played in 1904, was the first official match for both teams and the first official football match between independent countries on the European continent.<ref name="belfrares"/> Belgium maintained the better record with most wins over the succeeding 100 years, but since 2018 the gap has closed with 5 successive losses to France.<ref name="belfrares"/>

