Numerous former and current [[Belgium national football team home stadium#List of home stadiums|venues in 11 urban areas]] have hosted Belgium's home matches.<ref name="results"/> Most of these matches have been played in [[Brussels]] on the [[Heysel Plateau|Heysel/Heizel Plateau]], on the site of the present-day [[King Baudouin Stadium]]—a multipurpose facility with a seating capacity of 50,122.<ref>{{cite web |title=History King Baudouin Stadium |publisher=[[Royal Belgian Football Association|RBFA]] |access-date=9 May 2015 |url=http://www.belgianfootball.be/en/history-king-baudouin-stadium |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626115747/http://www.belgianfootball.be/en/history-king-baudouin-stadium |archive-date=26 June 2016}}</ref> Its field also hosts the team's final trainings before domestic matches. Since 2007, most physical preparation takes place at the National Football Centre in [[Tubize]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Duivels trainen voor het eerst in Tubeke |trans-title=Devils train for the first time in Tubeke |first=Ludo |last=Vandewalle |newspaper=[[De Standaard]] |language=nl |date=4 September 2007 |access-date=18 May 2015 |url=http://www.standaard.be/cnt/501gpofb |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626115835/http://www.standaard.be/cnt/501gpofb |archive-date=26 June 2016}}</ref> or at [[RSC Anderlecht|Anderlecht]]'s training ground in the [[Anderlecht|Neerpede]] quarter.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nieuwsblad.be/sportwereld/cnt/dmf20130323_052 |title=Rode Duivels trainen ontspannen in Neerpede |trans-title=Red Devils train relaxed in Neerpede |newspaper=[[Het Nieuwsblad]] |author=arvn |language=nl |date=23 March 2013 |access-date=31 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200920063701/https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20130323_052 |archive-date=20 September 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20150831_01841778 |title=Bosniërs trainen al eerste keer op Belgische bodem |trans-title=Bosnians train first time on Belgian soil already |newspaper=[[De Standaard]] |language=nl |author=vml |date=31 August 2015 |access-date=31 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151121040725/http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20150831_01841778 |archive-date=21 November 2015}}</ref> Apart from Belgian home friendlies, at the international level Belgium's national stadium has also hosted six European Championship matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/match/3838--west-germany-vs-ussr/ |title=UEFA Euro 1972 – History – Germany-USSR |publisher=[[UEFA]] |date=3 October 2003 |access-date=12 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626120301/http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season%3D1972/matches/round%3D186/match%3D3838/index.html |archive-date=26 June 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/00e-final.html |title=European Championship 2000 – Full Details Final Tournament |first=Pierre |last=Winkler |date=17 January 2004 |access-date= 12 August 2015 |website=[[RSSSF]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626120345/http://www.rsssf.com/tables/00e-final.html |archive-date=26 June 2016}}</ref>

In 1930, for the country's centennial, the venue was inaugurated as the Jubilee Stadium with an unofficial match between Belgium and the Netherlands.<ref name="DerbyBelNed"/> At that time, the stadium had a capacity of 75,000.<ref>{{cite news |title=België slaat Nederland met 4–1 |trans-title=Belgium beats Netherlands 4–1 |newspaper=[[Algemeen Handelsblad]] |via=[[Delpher]] |language=nl |url=http://www.delpher.nl/nl/kranten/view?coll=ddd&identifier=ddd%3A010661586%3Ampeg21%3Aa0317 |date=15 September 1930 |access-date=8 September 2015}}</ref> In 1946, it was renamed Heysel Stadium after its city quarter. This new name became associated with the tragedy preceding the [[1985 European Cup final]] between [[Juventus FC|Juventus]] and [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]; [[Heysel Stadium disaster|39 spectators died]] after riots in the then antiquated building.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2005/apr/03/newsstory.sport14 |title=Lost lives that saved a sport |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=15 June 2006 |author=[[Andrew Hussey|Hussey, Andrew]] |date=3 April 2005 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200726185004/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2005/apr/03/newsstory.sport14 |archive-date=26 July 2020}}</ref>{{sfn|Parrish|Nauright|2014|p=xxviii}} Three years after the disaster, plans were unveiled for a renovation;<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.delpher.nl/nl/kranten/view?coll=ddd&identifier=ddd%3A110610936%3Ampeg21%3Aa0572 |title=Heyzel-stadion wordt gesloopt |trans-title=Heyzel stadium to be demolished |newspaper=[[De Telegraaf]] |via=[[Delpher]] |language=nl |date=29 November 1988 |access-date=29 August 2015}}</ref> in 1995, after two years of work, the modernised stadium was named after the late [[Baudouin of Belgium|King Baudouin]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Stadion – Geschiedenis – Koning Boudewijnstadion |trans-title=Stadium – History – King Baudouin Stadium |url=http://www.prosportevent.be/nl/stadion/geschiedenis |publisher=Vzw Prosport Brussel |language=nl |access-date=12 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160626120701/http://www.prosportevent.be/nl/stadion/geschiedenis |archive-date=26 June 2016}}</ref> In May 2013, the Brussels-Capital Region announced that the King Baudouin Stadium would be replaced by [[Eurostadium]], elsewhere on the Heysel Plateau;<ref>{{cite news |title=Koning Boudewijnstadion wordt afgebroken |trans-title=King Baudouin Stadium to be demolished |newspaper=[[De Standaard]] |first=Geert |last=Sels |language=nl |date=25 May 2013 |access-date=9 July 2013 |url=https://www.standaard.be/cnt/DMF20130525_00597916 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200729020921/https://www.standaard.be/cnt/DMF20130525_00597916 |archive-date=29 July 2020}}</ref> in 2018, however, the plans for the new stadium were cancelled definitively.<ref>{{cite news |title=Brussel geeft de doodsteek aan Eurostadion |trans-title=Brussels gives deathblow to Eurostadium |newspaper=[[Het Nieuwsblad]] |language=nl |date=26 March 2018 |access-date=3 June 2018 |url=https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20180326_03430758 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326213404/https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20180326_03430758 |archive-date=26 March 2018}}</ref>

==Results and fixtures==
{{See also|Belgium national football team results|Belgium national football team records and statistics}}
{{As of|2026|6|2}}, the complete official match record of the Belgian national team comprises [[Belgium national football team results|861 matches]]: 382 wins, 182 draws and 297 losses.{{efn|name=fifa_unrec|Caps and goals against [[Romania national football team|Romania]] on 15 (actually 14) November 2012, against [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]] on 26 May 2014 and against [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]] on 5 June 2017 were counted by [http://www.belgianfootball.be/nl/alle-rode-duivels RBFA] but are not officially recognised by FIFA – the former two due to an excessive number of [[Substitute (association football)|substitutions]] according to the Laws of the Game,<ref name="UnrecMatch1">{{cite web |url=https://eu-football.info/_match.php?id=3770 |title=Football MATCH: 14.11.2012 (Romania v Belgium) |publisher=EU Football |access-date=17 November 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200726183008/https://eu-football.info/_match.php?id=3770 |archive-date=26 July 2020}}</ref><ref name="UnrecMatch2">{{cite web |url=https://eu-football.info/_match.php?id=925 |title=Football MATCH: 26.05.2014 (Belgium v Luxembourg) |publisher=EU Football |access-date=17 November 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200919102239/https://eu-football.info/_match.php?id=925 |archive-date=19 September 2020}}</ref><ref name="FArules">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefa.com/football-rules-governance/laws/football-11-11/law-3---the-number-of-players |title=Rules & Governance – Law 3: The number of players |publisher=[[The Football Association|The FA]] |access-date=25 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20141025102228/http://www.thefa.com/football-rules-governance/laws/football-11-11/law-3---the-number-of-players |archive-date=25 October 2014 }}</ref> the latter because the Belgian and Czech football federations were too late in requesting an official match.<ref name="Czechmatch">{{cite news |url=http://sporza.be/cm/sporza/voetbal/Rode_Duivels/1.2997051 |title=Welles-nietesspel rond oefenmatch tegen Tsjechië: Daarom was het geen officiële wedstrijd  |trans-title=Yes or no game about friendly against Czech Republic: this is why it was no official match |language=nl |newspaper=[[Sporza]] |date=6 June 2017 |access-date=6 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612185054/http://archief.sporza.be/cm/sporza/voetbal/Rode_Duivels/1.2997051 |archive-date=12 June 2018 }}</ref>}}<ref name="results"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://eu-football.info/_matches.php?id=21 |title=Belgium football results |access-date=8 April 2021 |website=EU-Football.info}}</ref> During these matches, the team scored 1,557 times and conceded 1,329 goals. Belgium's highest winning margin is nine goals, which has been achieved on four occasions: against [[Zambia national football team|Zambia]] in 1994 (9–0), twice against [[San Marino national football team|San Marino]] in 2001 (10–1) and 2019 (9–0), and against [[Gibraltar national football team|Gibraltar]] in 2017 (9–0).<ref name="results">{{cite web |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tablesb/belg-intres.html |title=Belgium – List of International Matches |first=Karel |last=Stokkermans |access-date=4 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701150657/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesb/belg-intres.html |archive-date=1 July 2016 |website=[[RSSSF]] |url-status=live}}</ref> Their longest winning streak is 12 wins, and their highest unbeaten record is 23 consecutive official matches.{{efn|This streak started in September 2016 and does not include the friendly win against [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]] on 5 June 2017; this match is not FIFA-recognised since the Belgian and Czech football federations were too late in asking that it would be official.<ref name="Czechmatch"/>}}<ref name="results"/>

