==Competitive record==
{{See also|Belgium national football team records and statistics#Achievements|l1=Achievements}}

===FIFA World Cup===
{{Main|Belgium at the FIFA World Cup}}
Belgium failed to progress past the first round in their first five World Cup participations. After two scoreless defeats at the [[1930 FIFA World Cup|inaugural World Cup]] in 1930,<ref name="rsssf30"/> the team scored in their first round knockout matches in the [[1934 FIFA World Cup|1934]] and [[1938 FIFA World Cup|1938 editions]].<ref name="rsssf34">{{cite web |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/34full.html |title=World Cup 1934 finals |access-date=27 August 2015 |website=[[RSSSF]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701145038/http://www.rsssf.com/tables/34full.html |archive-date=1 July 2016}}</ref><ref name="rsssf38"/> In 1954, they drew with England 4–4 after extra time,<ref name="rsssf54"/> and in 1970, they won their first World Cup match, against [[El Salvador national football team|El Salvador]] (3–0).<ref name="rsssf70"/>

From 1982 until 2002, Belgium qualified for six successive World Cups, advancing past the first round five times.<ref name="BBC230514"/> In the 1982 FIFA World Cup opener, Belgium beat [[1978 FIFA World Cup|defending champions]] Argentina 1–0. Their tournament ended in the second group stage, after a [[Poland national football team|Polish]] hat-trick by [[Zbigniew Boniek]] and a 0–1 loss against the [[Soviet Union national football team|Soviet Union]].<ref name="rsssf82"/>
[[File:Eeuubelgica1930.JPG|thumb|left|upright=1.2|United States–Belgium in 1930 was the joint first ever World Cup match.|alt=Match phase with aerial play]]
At Mexico 1986, the Belgian team achieved their then best-ever World Cup run at the time. In the knockout phase as [[Glossary of association football terms#U|underdogs]] they beat the Soviet Union after [[Overtime (sports)|extra time]] 4–3;<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://keepingscore.blogs.time.com/2010/06/02/top-10-world-cup-games/slide/3-belgium-4-3-ussr-1986/ |title=Top 10 World Cup Games – 3. Belgium 4–3 USSR 1986 |first=Glen |last=Levy |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=18 May 2010 |access-date=25 April 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701145129/http://keepingscore.blogs.time.com/2010/06/02/top-10-world-cup-games/slide/3-belgium-4-3-ussr-1986/ |archive-date=1 July 2016}}</ref> the unnoticed offside position of Jan Ceulemans, during the initial ninety minutes, allowed him to equalise the match at 2–2 and enter extra time.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nieuwsblad.be/sportwereld/cnt/dmf20140621_01150053 |title='Duivelsvloek' houdt al 28 jaar stand tegen Rusland, morgen ook? |trans-title='Devil curse' already lasts for 28 years against Russia, tomorrow as well? |newspaper=[[Het Nieuwsblad]] |author=vml |language=nl |date=21 June 2014 |access-date=20 September 2015}}</ref> They also beat [[Spain national football team|Spain]], in a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]] after a 1–1 draw, but lost to eventual champions Argentina in the semi-finals 2–0, and France in the third-place match 4–2.<ref name="rsssf86">{{cite web |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/86full.html |title=World Cup 1986 finals |access-date=27 August 2015 |website=[[RSSSF]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701145313/http://www.rsssf.com/tables/86full.html |archive-date=1 July 2016}}</ref>

In 1990, Belgium dominated periods of their round of 16 match against England;{{sfn|Edworthy|1997|pp=138–139}} Enzo Scifo and Jan Ceulemans hit the [[Glossary of association football terms#W|woodwork]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/gh92s49sk |title=26 juni 1990: de dag dat de goden blind waren |trans-title=26 June 1990: the day the gods were blind |language=nl |newspaper=[[Het Nieuwsblad]] |first=Michaël |last=Van Damme |date=26 June 2010 |access-date=19 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160721110630/http://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/gh92s49sk |archive-date=21 July 2016}}</ref> [[David Platt]]'s [[Volley (association football)|volley]] in the final minute of extra time, described as "nearly blind" by Richard Witzig,{{sfn|Witzig|2006|p=167}} avoided an apparently goalless draw and led to the sudden elimination of the Belgians.<ref name="rsssf90">{{cite web|url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/90full.html |title=World Cup 1990 finals |access-date=19 July 2016 |website=[[RSSSF]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090421181034/http://www.rsssf.com/tables/90full.html |archive-date=21 April 2009 }}</ref>

In 1994, a 3–2 defeat to defending champions [[Germany national football team|Germany]] saw Belgium go out in the second round again.<ref name="rsssf94"/> Afterwards, the entire Belgian delegation criticised referee [[Kurt Röthlisberger]] for not awarding a penalty for a [[Fouls and misconduct (association football)|foul]] on Belgian [[Josip Weber]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.trouw.nl/tr/nl/5009/Archief/article/detail/2679500/1994/07/04/Belgen-furieus-op-Rothlisberger.dhtml |newspaper=[[Trouw]] |first=Fred |last=Buddenberg |title=Belgen furieus op Röthlisberger |trans-title=Belgians furious with Röthlisberger |language=nl |date=4 July 1994 |access-date=20 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701145344/http://www.trouw.nl/tr/nl/5009/Archief/article/detail/2679500/1994/07/04/Belgen-furieus-op-Rothlisberger.dhtml |archive-date=1 July 2016}}</ref> Three draws in the group stage of the 1998 World Cup were insufficient for Belgium to reach the knockout stage.<ref name="rsssf98" /> With two draws, the 2002 tournament started poorly for Belgium, but they won the decisive group match against Russia 3–2. In the second round, they faced eventual champions Brazil; Belgium lost 2–0 after Marc Wilmots' headed opening goal was disallowed due to a "phantom foul" on [[Roque Júnior]], as Witzig named it.<ref name="rsssf2002">{{cite web |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/2002full.html |title=World Cup 2002 – Match Details |first=Erlan |last=Manaschev |date=3 July 2008 |access-date=27 August 2015 |website=[[RSSSF]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701145417/http://www.rsssf.com/tables/2002full.html |archive-date=1 July 2016}}</ref>{{sfn|Witzig|2006|p=289}}

In 2014, Belgium beat all their group opponents by only one goal,<ref name="rsssf2014">{{cite web |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/2014full.html |title=World Cup 2014 – Match Details |first=Neil |last=Morrison |date=24 July 2014 |access-date=27 August 2015 |website=[[RSSSF]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701145500/http://www.rsssf.com/tables/2014full.html |archive-date=1 July 2016}}</ref> and played an entertaining round of 16 match against the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/belgium-vs-u-s-was-the-best-match-of-the-world-cup-so-far/ |title=U.S. vs. Belgium Was the Best Match of the World Cup So Far |author=[[Carl Bialik|Bialik, Carl]] |publisher=[[FiveThirtyEight]] |date=10 July 2014 |access-date=25 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701145621/http://fivethirtyeight.com/datalab/belgium-vs-u-s-was-the-best-match-of-the-world-cup-so-far/ |archive-date=1 July 2016}}</ref> in which American goalkeeper [[Tim Howard]] made 15 saves.{{efn|FIFA's initial match statistics showed 16 saves, and many news sources continue to use this number. The official FIFA statistics were updated on 5 July 2014 to show 15 saves.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://resources.fifa.com/mm/document/tournament/competition/02/39/98/53/eng_56_0701_bel-usa_usa_playerstatistics_neutral.pdf |title=Official FIFA statistics, updated 5 July 2014 |publisher=[[FIFA]] |date=5 July 2014 |access-date=29 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701145714/http://resources.fifa.com/mm/document/tournament/competition/02/39/98/53/eng_56_0701_bel-usa_usa_playerstatistics_neutral.pdf |archive-date=1 July 2016}}</ref>}} However, they defeated the U.S. 2–1 in extra time.<ref name="rsssf2014" /> In a balanced quarter-finals, Argentina eliminated Belgium, after a 1–0 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/round=255953/match=300186504/statistics.html#nosticky |title=2014 FIFA World Cup Brazil – Matches – Argentina-Belgium – Live Statistics |publisher=[[FIFA]] |access-date=27 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701145935/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/round%3D255953/match%3D300186504/statistics.html |archive-date=1 July 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

At the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018 World Cup]], Belgium started with five consecutive victories (including [[2018 FIFA World Cup Group G|group wins]] over [[Panama national football team|Panama]], [[Tunisia national football team|Tunisia]] and England). In the round of 16 match against [[Japan national football team|Japan]], Belgium were down 2–0,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lucarne-opposee.fr/index.php/actualite/express/7032-coupe-du-monde-2019-nouvelles-d-asie-2|title=Coupe du Monde 2022 : nouvelles d'Asie|website=Lucarne opposée|date=2 July 2019|accessdate=29 January 2022|author=Boris Ghanem|language=fr|archive-date=29 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220129191337/https://lucarne-opposee.fr/index.php/actualite/express/7032-coupe-du-monde-2019-nouvelles-d-asie-2|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://lucarne-opposee.fr/index.php/culture-foot/l-autre-japon/6698-japon-football-japonais-quel-avenir|title=Japon : Football japonais, quel avenir ?|website=Lucarne opposée|date=29 March 2019|accessdate=29 January 2022|author=Ibrahim Ouazzani|language=fr|archive-date=29 January 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220129191336/https://lucarne-opposee.fr/index.php/culture-foot/l-autre-japon/6698-japon-football-japonais-quel-avenir|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.journaldujapon.com/2018/07/14/coupe-du-monde-2018-bilan/|title=Coupe du Monde 2018 : folie et cruauté|website=Journal du Japon|date=14 July 2018|accessdate=29 January 2022|author=Martin Karpinski|language=fr}}</ref> eventually turning the tide and eventually winning 3–2 with goals from [[Jan Vertonghen]] and late substitutes [[Marouane Fellaini]] and [[Nacer Chadli]]. Belgium then defeated World Cup favourites Brazil 2–1 on the back of an early [[Fernandinho (footballer, born May 1985)|Fernandinho]] [[own goal]] and a goal by [[Kevin De Bruyne]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Rogers |first=Martin |title=Brazil's bizarre own-goal gives Belgium the lead |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/sports/soccer/worldcup/2018/07/06/belgium-brazil-goal-fernandinho-world-cup/763855002/ |date=6 July 2018 |access-date=7 July 2018 |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |publisher=[[Gannett]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Wilson |first=Jonathan |title=Brazil knocked out of World Cup by Kevin De Bruyne and brilliant Belgium |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/jul/06/brazil-belgium-world-cup-quarter-final-match-report |date=6 July 2018 |access-date=7 July 2018 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian News and Media Limited]]}}</ref> and reached the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|semi-finals]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Rogers |first=Martin |title=Belgium fights off Brazil's comeback to reach World Cup semifinals |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/sports/soccer/worldcup/2018/07/06/belgium-brazil-world-cup/764264002/ |date=6 July 2018 |access-date=7 July 2018 |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |publisher=[[Gannett]]}}</ref> Belgium lost to [[France national football team|France]] 0–1 in the semi-finals, but rebounded to win 2–0 in their second victory over England in the tournament to secure third place and the best ever World Cup result for the Belgian national team. 
